<body class="ignore-math">
<h4 class="heading"><span class="type">Paragraph</span></h4>
<p>For example, consider the integral</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">We could let <span class="process-math">\(u = x\)</span> so that <span class="process-math">\(\dx{u} = 2x \dx{x}\)</span> . This would lead to</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}= \int u\sqrt{u^{3/2}+1}\left(\frac{\dx{u}}{2x}\right) = \frac12\int\frac{u\sqrt{u^{3/2}+1}}{x}\dx{u}.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">Notice that we can bring the <span class="process-math">\(1/2\)</span> outside the integral because it is a constant, but since  <span class="process-math">\(\frac{1}{x}\)</span> is not a constant (it depends on <span class="process-math">\(u\)</span>) we cannot do the same with with it. We could rewrite <span class="process-math">\(x = \sqrt{u}\)</span> , so that</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{align*}
\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x} = \frac12\int\frac{u\sqrt{u^{3/2}}}{\sqrt{u}}\dx{u} \amp= \frac12 \int\sqrt{u}\sqrt{x^{3/2}+1}\dx{u}\\
\amp=\frac12\int\sqrt{u^{5/2}+u}\dx{u}.
\end{align*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">This is all correct, but leads to an integral far worse than the original, especially if you notice that <span class="process-math">\(x\)</span> is <span class="process-math">\(3\)</span> “almost” the derivative of <span class="process-math">\(x + 1\text{.}\)</span> It is off by a factor of <span class="process-math">\(3\text{,}\)</span> but as we’ve seen, constants can be brought outside of the integral, so this is not really a problem. So let’s make <span class="process-math">\(y = x + 1\)</span> , so that <span class="process-math">\(\dx{y} = 3x \dx{x}\text{.}\)</span>  Thus</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{align*}
\int x^2\sqrt{x^3+1}\dx{x}\amp=\int x^2\sqrt{y}\left(\frac{\dx{y}}{3x^2}\right)\\
\amp=\frac13\int y^{1/2}\dx{y}\\
\amp=\frac13\left(\frac{y^{3/2}}{3/2}\right)+c\\
\amp=\frac29\left(x^3+1\right)^{3/2}+c
\end{align*}
</div>
<span class="incontext"><a href="section-4.html#p-81" class="internal">in-context</a></span>
</body>
</html>
